The `@ConditionalOnProperty` enables bean registration only if an environment property is present and has a specific value.

This means that you cannot use it to check if the property is present in the `application.yml` or `application.properties` file.

I think you have 2 options


----------
**Option 1: Add a new property in the application properties**

You can add a new property in the application properties file. 

For example:
```yaml
my:
  redis:
    enabled: true
    connections:
      - name: redis-1
        address: 127.0.0.1:6379
        mode: master
      - name: redis-2
        address: 127.0.0.1:6479
        mode: slave
        ofSlave: redis-1
      - name: redis-3
        address: 127.0.0.1:6579
        mode: slave
        ofSlave: redis-1
```

The new property `my.redis.enabled` is not required to be mapped by the object used to map the connection properties, so it should not affect how you read the configuration. 

Now you can use `my.redis.enabled`
```java
@ConditionalOnProperty(&quot;my.redis.enabled&quot;)
public class MyRedisAutoConfiguration {}
```

This is the simplest and better solution IMO


----------
**Option 2: Implement Custom Condition**

You can map the configuration in a class, for example:

```java
@ConfigurationProperties(prefix = &quot;my.redis&quot;)
public class RedisConnectionProperties {
    
    private Map&lt;String, String&gt; connections;

    public Map&lt;String, String&gt; getConnections() {
        return connections;
    }

    public void setConnections(Map&lt;String, String&gt; connections) {
        this.connections = connections;
    }

}
```

And then implement a custom condition that will check if the `Map` of Redis connection that was mapped to `RedisConnectionProperties` is empty:

```java
public class RedisConnection implements Condition {

  @Override
  public boolean matches(ConditionContext context, AnnotatedTypeMetadata metadata) {
    RedisConnectionProperties config = Binder.get(context.getEnvironment())
        .bind(&quot;my.redis&quot;,RedisConnectionProperties.class)
        .orElse(null);
    return config != null &amp;&amp; config.getConnections() != null &amp;&amp; !config.getConnections().isEmpty();
  }
}
```

Finally, you can use this condition on `MyRedisAutoConfiguration`:

```java
@Conditional(RedisConnection.class)
public class MyRedisAutoConfiguration {}
```

