##### 1. You can separate a channel from a session, so it&#39;s safer to explicit close the channel

```
Session session = null;
ChannelExec channel = null;
Session session2 = null;
ChannelExec2 channel = null;

try {
  session = new JSch().getSession(username, host, port);
  ...
  channel = (ChannelExec) session.openChannel(&quot;exec&quot;);
  ...
  session2 = new JSch().getSession(username, host, port);
  channel.setSession(session2);
  ...
} finally {
  if (session != null) {
	session.disconnect();
  }
  if (channel != null) {
	channel.disconnect();
  }
}
try {
  channel2 = (ChannelExec) session.openChannel(&quot;exec&quot;);
  ...
} finally {
  if (session2 != null) {
	session2.disconnect();
  }
  if (channel2 != null) {
	channel2.disconnect();
  }
}
```
##### 2. `disconnect` calls [close][1], which may throw an `IOException`.  
So to be safe, you should handle this case.

```
Session session = null;
ChannelExec channel = null;
try {
  session = new JSch().getSession(username, host, port);
  ...
  channel = (ChannelExec) session.openChannel(&quot;exec&quot;);
  ...
} catch(Exception ex) {
  ex.printStacktrace();
} finally {
  try {
    if (session != null) {
      session.disconnect();
    }
  } catch(Exception e1) {
    e1.printStackTrace();
  }
  try {
    if (channel != null) {
     channel.disconnect();
    }
  } catch(Exception e2) {
    e2.printStacktrace();
  }
}
```
##### 3. Examples are often simplified to focus on a use case. So don&#39;t take everything in them as gospel.


  [1]: https://github.com/rtyley/jsch/blob/master/src/com/jcraft/jsch/Channel.java#L341

